\b 19. What is box model?\par
\b0\par
\tab The box model is a fundamental concept in CSS that describes the layout of elements on a webpage. It consists of four components: content, padding, border, and margin. These components create a rectangular box around every element, and their sizes can be adjusted using CSS properties.\par
\par
1. Content: The actual content of the box, where text and images appear.\par
2. Padding: Clears an area around the content, inside the border. It is transparent.\par
3. Border: A border surrounding the padding (if any) and content.\par
4. Margin: Clears an area outside the border. It separates the element from other elements in the document.\par
\par
\par
\b 20. What is flex model?\par
\b0\par
\tab The Flexbox  model is a layout model in CSS designed to provide a more efficient way to design and distribute space among items in a container, even when the size of the items is unknown or dynamic. Flexbox allows for easier alignment and distribution of space along a single axis (either horizontally or vertically) and is particularly useful for designing responsive and dynamic layouts.\par
\par
\par
1. `display: flex;`: Turns an element into a flex container.\par
2. `flex-direction`: Specifies the direction of the flex container's main axis (row or  column).\par
3. `justify-content`: Aligns items along the main axis.\par
4. `align-items`: Aligns items along the cross axis.\par
\par
